  "output": "## Findings\n\nThis is a pure Python async pipeline (job-board scraper → filter → SQLite dedup → notify) — **there's no React/frontend code**, so \"unnecessary re-renders\" doesn't apply. I found the equivalent CPU/IO issues in the Python layer instead. `sources.yaml` configures 132 sources, several paginated up to 40 pages × 10-20 jobs/page, so a single run can easily produce several thousand `Job` objects flowing through the code below — these aren't theoretical.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (`Store.diff`, the biggest win)\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    for job in jobs:\n        row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\",\n                          (job.key,)).fetchone()   # <-- one round-trip per job\n        if row is None:\n            self._insert(cur, job, now)            # <-- one execute per job\n        else:\n            ...\n            self._update(cur, job, now)             # <-- one execute per job\n```\n\nFor every one of potentially thousands of jobs, this does a separate `SELECT`, then a separate `INSERT`/`UPDATE`. That's up to 2N sequential SQLite round-trips per pipeline run.\n\n**Fix** — one bulk `SELECT ... WHERE key IN (...)` to build a lookup dict, then batch writes with `executemany`:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing = {}\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):  # stay under SQLite's ~999 param limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 900]\n        q = f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({','.join('?' * len(chunk))})\"\n        existing.update({r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"] for r in cur.execute(q, chunk)})\n\n    new, changed, unchanged_rows, insert_rows, update_rows = [], [], [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job); insert_rows.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); update_rows.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        else:\n            unchanged_rows.append({\"now\": now, \"key\": job.key})\n\n    if insert_rows:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key,:source,...,:now,:now)\"\"\", insert_rows)\n    if update_rows:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\"\"\", update_rows)\n    if unchanged_rows:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=:now WHERE key=:key\", unchanged_rows)\n\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(N) round-trips into O(N/900 + 3) statements.\n\n### 2. Missing index — `store.py:127-135` (`added_since`)\n\n```python\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_jobs_company ON jobs(company);\n```\n\nThere's an index on `company` but `added_since` filters and sorts on `first_seen` (`WHERE first_seen > ? ORDER BY first_seen, company, title`), which does a full table scan + sort as the table grows. This is hit on every `agent.py db-new` scan.\n\n**Fix:**\n```sql\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_jobs_first_seen ON jobs(first_seen);\n```\nAdd it to `_SCHEMA` in store.py:10-32.\n\n### 3. Redundant computation — `filters.py:11-27` (regex list rebuilt per job)\n\n```python\ndef match(job: Job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):   # rebuilds list every call\n    if include:\n        if not any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(include)):  # rebuilds list every call\n```\n\n`filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per job, and `match()` rebuilds the `include`/`exclude` pattern lists from scratch each time — for thousands of jobs against the same static rule set. (Python's internal `re` cache avoids literally recompiling the regex engine, but you still pay list-comprehension + cache-dict-lookup overhead per job, per keyword.)\n\n**Fix** — compile once in `filter_jobs` and pass compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef match(job: Job, *, include: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          exclude: list[re.Pattern] | None = None, ...) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    cutoff = ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=rules.get(\"locations\"), cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\n\n### 4. Redundant hash computation — `models.py:66-75` / `store.py:60-97`\n\n`content_hash` is a `@property` that runs `sha256` on every access. In `Store.diff`, `job.content_hash` is computed once for the comparison, then `to_row()` (called inside `_insert`/`_update`) computes it **again** via `asdict(self)` + hash. That's 2 SHA-256 hashes per job instead of 1.\n\n**Fix:** compute it once per job in `diff()` and pass it through, or switch to `functools.cached_property` (works fine even on a `@dataclass(slots=True)` if you add `__dict__` via `slots=False` for that field, or simpler: just compute once locally in `diff()` as shown in fix #1 above — `to_row()` already needs it, so pass the hash in rather than recomputing).\n\n### 5. Sequential blocking I/O in notify — `notify.py:105-109`\n\n```python\ndef dispatch(new, changed):\n    for fn in NOTIFIERS:\n        fn(new, changed)   # slack, webhook, email(SMTP), sms(Twilio) — all synchronous httpx.post\n```\n\nEverything else in the pipeline is async (`fetch_all` uses `asyncio.gather` with a semaphore), but `dispatch` runs four blocking network calls back-to-back on the event loop thread via `run_sync`/`asyncio.run`. Each one (Slack webhook, generic webhook, SMTP, Twilio) can take 100ms–several seconds; worst case they serialize to several seconds of dead time per run.\n\n**Fix:** run notifiers concurrently via a thread pool (they're blocking libs) or convert to `httpx.AsyncClient`:\n```python\nasync def dispatch_async(new, changed):\n    loop = asyncio.get_running_loop()\n    await asyncio.gather(*(\n        loop.run_in_executor(None, _safe_call, fn, new, changed) for fn in NOTIFIERS\n    ))\n```\nand await it from `pipeline.run` instead of the current synchronous `dispatch(new, changed)` at pipeline.py:44.\n\n### 6. No memory leaks found\n\n- `httpx.AsyncClient` lifecycle in `fetch_all` (fetchers.py:1126-1147) is correctly scoped with `try/finally` + `aclose()`.\n- `Store` is used via context manager (`with Store(...) as store`) in pipeline.py and agent.py, closing the sqlite3 connection properly.\n- No unbounded module-level caches or growing global state anywhere in the codebase.\n\n### Not applicable\n- **React re-renders**: no frontend code in this repo.\n- **Caching opportunities beyond #3/#4**: the fetchers are one-shot-per-run HTTP calls to external ATS APIs (Greenhouse, Lever, Workday, etc.) with pagination-loop dedup already handled via `seen` sets — there's no repeated-computation caching opportunity there worth adding (adding an HTTP cache would risk staleness, which conflicts with the tool's whole purpose of detecting *new* postings).\n\n### Priority\n1. Fix #1 (`Store.diff` N+1) — highest impact, directly scales with job volume every run.\n2. Fix #2 (missing index) — cheap, compounds as `jobs.db` grows.\n3. Fix #5 (serial notify) — real latency on every run once fresh jobs are found.\n4. Fix #3/#4 — minor CPU savings, easy wins, low risk.\n",
